 And - not only that, that woman'd make soup - where people would throw all the bits out. They used to use a lot of bacon, and she used to cut all the rinds off and boil it all down, the bones of - out of the bacon, and - it - then she'd get the peas and 
put 'em in and the vegetables and it was all strained. Yes. And - I could take that - what was thick - home to my mother for her chickens. So there was no - no wasted.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15954610 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14885319\charrsid3419878 They had a dining room?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9640500 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14885319\charrsid3419878 Yes, oh yes, a breakfast room, dining room, and a - an
d I had to wait - very often she had an at home day. I used to like that. And - take the tea trolley in, of course I used to have special little - hat - cap and apron for that, all lace on it. And I had to buy my own mind. Oh yes. Mm. And - I was lucky li
k
e because my mother had a black blouse, and she - got somebody to stitch it on and make the thick skirt and of course - mm. Mm. But - I enjoyed every minute, and if I was young enough and they were - living, I'd go back there tomorrow. I had a beautiful l
etter off of the master when the missus died because I sent and told him how sorry I was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15954610 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14885319\charrsid3419878 What sort of cooking equipment was there?
